T1  - Fixed-rate deposit insurance and risk-shifting behavior at commercial banks
AU  - Duan, Jin-Chuan
AU  - Moreau, Arthur F.
AU  - Sealey, C.W.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 16
IS  - 4
SP  - 715
EP  - 742
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/08/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(92)90004-J
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669290004J
AB  - Fixed-rate deposit insurance is thought to provide banks with an incentive to shift risk to the FDIC, thereby expropriating wealth. Banks can achieve these wealth transfers by increasing their overall risk and thus increasing the actuarial value of the deposit insurance. In this paper, the risk-shifting hypothesis is tested on a sample of US banks. An option-based methodology is used to price each bank's actuarial liability to the FDIC. Statistical tests are then conducted to determine if banks have been successful in manipulating risk in such a way as to increase these liabilities. The results suggest that risk-shifting is not widespread, although there are notable exceptions.
ER  - 

